  "local_port": 57538,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best books of all time?",
  "response": "The \"best\" books of all time can vary depending on personal tastes and criteria, but some consistently rank highly on various lists compiled by critics, readers, and literary organizations. Here\u2019s a selection of highly acclaimed books across different genres and time periods:\n\n### Classics\n1. **\"To Kill a Mockingbird\" by Harper Lee**\n   - A powerful story about racial injustice and moral growth in the American South.\n\n2. **\"1984\" by George Orwell**\n   - A dystopian novel about surveillance, propaganda, and totalitarianism.\n\n3. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen**\n   - A timeless romance novel exploring themes of class, social status, and love.\n\n4. **\"The Great Gatsby\" by F. Scott Fitzgerald**\n   - A tragic exploration of the American Dream set in the Roaring Twenties.\n\n5. **\"Moby-Dick\" by Herman Melville**\n   - An epic tale of obsession and revenge set on the high seas.\n\n### Modern Fiction\n1. **\"Beloved\" by Toni Morrison**\n   - A haunting novel about the legacy of slavery and its impact on personal lives.\n\n2. **\"One Hundred Years of Solitude\" by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez**\n   - A masterpiece of magical realism chronicling the multi-generational story of the Buend\u00eda family.\n\n3. **\"The Handmaid's Tale\" by Margaret Atwood**\n   - A dystopian novel about a future where women are subjugated and used for reproductive purposes.\n\n4. **\"The Remains of the Day\" by Kazuo Ishiguro**\n   - A poignant story about duty, dignity, and the passage of time, told through the eyes of a butler.\n\n5. **\"Americanah\" by Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie**\n   - A powerful exploration of race, identity, and immigration through the lives of two Nigerians.\n\n### Non-Fiction\n1. **\"The Diary of a Young Girl\" by Anne Frank**\n   - A poignant and personal account of a Jewish girl's life in hiding during the Holocaust.\n\n2. **\"A Brief History of Time\" by Stephen Hawking**\n   - An accessible introduction to the theories and discoveries of modern cosmology.\n\n3. **\"The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks\" by Rebecca Skloot**\n   - An eye-opening exploration of medical ethics and the story of an African-American woman whose cells were used in scientific research.\n\n4. **\"In Cold Blood\" by Truman Capote**\n   - A true crime novel that delves into the brutal murder of a Kansas family and the subsequent investigation.\n\n5. **\"A People\u2019s History of the United States\" by Howard Zinn**\n   - A comprehensive and alternative view of American history from the perspective of the marginalized.\n\n### Science Fiction/Fantasy\n1. **\"Dune\" by Frank Herbert**\n   - A sweeping epic set on the desert planet Arrakis, exploring themes of politics, religion, and ecology.\n\n2. **\"The Lord of the Rings\" by J.R.R. Tolkien**\n   - A monumental work of fantasy literature that follows a hobbit's quest to destroy a powerful ring.\n\n3. **\"Brave New World\" by Aldous Huxley**\n   - A dystopian novel that envisions a future where individuality is suppressed through technological and social control.\n\n4. **\"Neuromancer\" by William Gibson**\n   - A groundbreaking cyberpunk novel that explores the intersection of technology and humanity.\n\n5. **\"The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy\" by Douglas Adams**\n   - A humorous science fiction series that takes readers on a wild journey through space.\n\nThese books are widely regarded as some of the greatest in their respective genres and have left a lasting impact on literature and popular culture.",
